8079 /* ---------------------------------------------------------- */
8080 /* Some useful macros for inline assembler instructions */
8081 /* ---------------------------------------------------------- */
8082 
8083 #define Nop() __builtin_nop()
8084 #define ClrWdt() {__asm__ volatile ("clrwdt");}
8085 #define Sleep() {__asm__ volatile ("pwrsav #0");}
8086 #define Idle() {__asm__ volatile ("pwrsav #1");}
8087 
8088 /*----------------------------------------------------------- */
8089 /* Some useful macros for allocating data memory */
8090 /*----------------------------------------------------------- */
8091 
8092 /* The following macros require an argument N that specifies */
8093 /* alignment. N must a power of two, minimum value = 2. */
8094 /* For example, to declare an uninitialized array in X memory */
8095 /* that is aligned to a 32 byte address: */
8096 /* */
8097 /* int _XBSS(32) xbuf[16]; */
8098 /* */
8099 #define _XBSS(N) __attribute__((space(xmemory),far,aligned(N)))
8100 #define _XDATA(N) __attribute__((space(xmemory),far,aligned(N)))
8101 #define _YBSS(N) __attribute__((space(ymemory),far,aligned(N)))
8102 #define _YDATA(N) __attribute__((space(ymemory),far,aligned(N)))
8103 
8104 /* The following macros do not require an argument. They can */
8105 /* be used to locate a variable in persistent data memory or */
8106 /* in near data memory. For example, to declare two variables */
8107 /* that retain their values across a device reset: */
8108 /* */
8109 /* int _PERSISTENT var1,var2; */
8110 /* */
8111 #define _PERSISTENT __attribute__((persistent))
8112 #define _NEAR __attribute__((near))
8113 
8114 /* ---------------------------------------------------------- */
8115 /* Some useful macros for declaring functions */
8116 /* ---------------------------------------------------------- */
8117 
8118 /* The following macros can be used to declare interrupt */
8119 /* service routines (ISRs). For example, to declare an ISR */
8120 /* for the timer1 interrupt: */
8121 /* */
8122 /* void _ISR _T1Interrupt(void); */
8123 /* */
8124 /* To declare an ISR for the SPI1 interrupt with fast */
8125 /* context save: */
8126 /* */
8127 /* void _ISRFAST _SPI1Interrupt(void); */
8128 /* */
8129 /* Note: ISRs will be installed into the interrupt vector */
8130 /* tables automatically if the reserved names listed in the */
8131 /* MPLAB C30 Compiler User's Guide (DS51284) are used. */
8132 /* */
8133 #define _ISR __attribute__((interrupt))
8134 #define _ISRFAST __attribute__((interrupt, shadow))
8135 
8136 /* ---------------------------------------------------------- */
8137 /* Some useful macros for changing the CPU IPL */
8138 /* ---------------------------------------------------------- */
8139 
8140 /* The following macros can be used to modify the current CPU */
8141 /* IPL. The definition of the macro may vary from device to */
8142 /* device. */
8143 /* */
8144 /* To safely set the CPU IPL, use SET_CPU_IPL(ipl); the */
8145 /* valid range of ipl is 0-7, it may be any expression. */
8146 /* */
8147 /* SET_CPU_IPL(7); */
8148 /* */
8149 /* To preserve the current IPL and save it use */
8150 /* SET_AND_SAVE_CPU_IPL(save_to, ipl); the valid range of ipl */
8151 /* is 0-7 and may be any expression, save_to should denote */
8152 /* some temporary storage. */
8153 /* */
8154 /* int old_ipl; */
8155 /* */
8156 /* SET_AND_SAVE_CPU_IPL(old_ipl, 7); */
8157 /* */
8158 /* The IPL can be restored with RESTORE_CPU_IPL(saved_to) */
8159 /* */
8160 /* RESTORE_CPU_IPL(old_ipl); */
8161 
8162 #define SET_CPU_IPL(ipl) { \
8163  int DISI_save; \
8164  \
8165  DISI_save = DISICNT; \
8166  asm volatile ("disi #0x3FFF"); \
8167  SRbits.IPL = ipl; \
8168  DISICNT = DISI_save; } (void) 0;
8169 
8170 #define SET_AND_SAVE_CPU_IPL(save_to, ipl) { \
8171  save_to = SRbits.IPL; \
8172  SET_CPU_IPL(ipl); } (void) 0;
8173 
8174 #define RESTORE_CPU_IPL(saved_to) SET_CPU_IPL(saved_to)
8175 
8176 
8177 
8178 /* -------------------------------------------------------- */
8179 /* Macros for setting device configuration registers */
8180 /* -------------------------------------------------------- */
8181 
8182 /* Register FICD (0x157f0) */
8183 
8184 extern __attribute__((space(prog))) int _FICD;
8185 #define _FICD(x) __attribute__((section("__FICD.sec"),space(prog))) int _FICD = (x);
8186 
8187 /*
8188 ** Only one invocation of FICD should appear in a project,
8189 ** at the top of a C source file (outside of any function).
8190 **
8191 ** The following constants can be used to set FICD.
8192 ** Multiple options may be combined, as shown:
8193 **
8194 ** _FICD( OPT1_ON & OPT2_OFF & OPT3_PLL )
8195 **
8196 ** ICD Communication Channel Select bits:
8197 ** ICS_NONE Reserved, do not use
8198 ** ICS_PGD3 Communicate on PGEC3 and PGED3
8199 ** ICS_PGD2 Communicate on PGEC2 and PGED2
8200 ** ICS_PGD1 Communicate on PGEC1 and PGED1
8201 **
8202 ** JTAG Enable bit:
8203 ** JTAGEN_OFF JTAG is disabled
8204 ** JTAGEN_ON JTAG is enabled
8205 **
8206 */
8207 
8208 #define ICS_NONE 0xFFFC
8209 #define ICS_PGD3 0xFFFD
8210 #define ICS_PGD2 0xFFFE
8211 #define ICS_PGD1 0xFFFF
8212 
8213 #define JTAGEN_OFF 0xFFDF
8214 #define JTAGEN_ON 0xFFFF
8215 
8216 /* Register FPOR (0x157f2) */
8217 
8218 extern __attribute__((space(prog))) int _FPOR;
8219 #define _FPOR(x) __attribute__((section("__FPOR.sec"),space(prog))) int _FPOR = (x);
8220 
8221 /*
8222 ** Only one invocation of FPOR should appear in a project,
8223 ** at the top of a C source file (outside of any function).
8224 **
8225 ** The following constants can be used to set FPOR.
8226 ** Multiple options may be combined, as shown:
8227 **
8228 ** _FPOR( OPT1_ON & OPT2_OFF & OPT3_PLL )
8229 **
8230 ** Alternate I2C1 pins:
8231 ** ALTI2C1_ON I2C1 mapped to ASDA1/ASCL1 pins
8232 ** ALTI2C1_OFF I2C1 mapped to SDA1/SCL1 pins
8233 **
8234 ** Alternate I2C2 pins:
8235 ** ALTI2C2_ON I2C2 mapped to ASDA2/ASCL2 pins
8236 ** ALTI2C2_OFF I2C2 mapped to SDA2/SCL2 pins
8237 **
8238 ** Watchdog Window Select bits:
